They're going for June.
I know.

245
00:17:32,450 --> 00:17:35,050
The clock is ticking.
Put Penny on.

246
00:17:39,350 --> 00:17:41,350
Guess what, Miss Moneypenny?

247
00:17:45,100 --> 00:17:46,450
Hold on, Penny.

248
00:17:48,900 --> 00:17:50,550
This shoe is stuck.

249
00:17:59,700 --> 00:18:01,950
Not my good shoes.

250
00:18:02,000 --> 00:18:03,550
Oh, my goodness.

251
00:18:09,350 --> 00:18:11,550
My new Gucci shoe.

252
00:18:11,650 --> 00:18:13,800
Come on!

253
00:18:21,750 --> 00:18:24,550
Oh, are you okay?
Are you okay?

254
00:18:27,100 --> 00:18:28,750
I'm great.

255
00:18:28,850 --> 00:18:31,150
- Okay.
- Where's my shoe?

256
00:18:31,200 --> 00:18:34,200
Your shoe?
You got it right here.

257
00:18:34,300 --> 00:18:36,900
Now talk to me.
How are you feeling?

258
00:18:36,950 --> 00:18:41,300
Are you experiencing any dizziness,
nausea, difficulty breathing?

259
00:18:43,100 --> 00:18:44,700
The breathing thing rings a bell.

260
00:18:46,800 --> 00:18:50,500
Then again, you are on top of me,
cutting off my air supply.

261
00:18:51,950 --> 00:18:55,200
Your mental clarity's excellent.
That's good. That's good.

262
00:18:56,300 --> 00:18:58,750
Don't appear to have a concussion.

263
00:18:58,800 --> 00:19:00,750
You took quite a fall.

264
00:19:00,800 --> 00:19:02,750
Why are you still on top of me?

265
00:19:07,450 --> 00:19:09,600
That's a good question.

266
00:19:09,650 --> 00:19:13,200
You see that dumpster there?
Seems that dumpster tried to kill you.

267
00:19:13,300 --> 00:19:16,400
You were standing in the middle of the
road, and it was coming right at you.

268
00:19:16,500 --> 00:19:18,950
Just take your time.
Sit up straight. You okay?

269
00:19:21,050 --> 00:19:22,500
You saved...

270
00:19:23,700 --> 00:19:25,200
my shoe.

271
00:19:26,450 --> 00:19:27,900
My life.

272
00:19:29,400 --> 00:19:32,500
Your shoe was what I was going for.
You just turned out to be a bonus.

273
00:19:32,550 --> 00:19:35,250
Come on. We're gonna try and get up.
Take your time.

274
00:19:35,300 --> 00:19:37,250
Take your time.

275
00:19:37,300 --> 00:19:39,400
Up.

276
00:19:39,500 --> 00:19:42,050
Here we go.
I got you. I got you.

277
00:19:44,500 --> 00:19:46,600
I got you, okay?

278
00:19:48,900 --> 00:19:52,400
You smell like sweet red plums...

279
00:19:52,400 --> 00:19:56,550
and grilled cheese sandwiches.

280
00:19:59,050 --> 00:20:01,150
Okay. Here you go.

281
00:20:01,300 --> 00:20:02,400
Aah, my thumb!

282
00:20:04,250 --> 00:20:06,950
Yeah, I get that all the time.
Thank you.

283
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:10,750
All right. Hold up!
All right.

284
00:20:11,800 --> 00:20:13,750
Yup, she's dead, all right.

285
00:20:13,800 --> 00:20:17,000
- You think she's going to heaven?
- Definitely.

286
00:20:17,050 --> 00:20:20,150
She's got the cleanest toes
I've ever seen.

287
00:20:20,250 --> 00:20:22,400
Where am I?

288
00:20:22,500 --> 00:20:26,350
You're at the children's ward
of St. Vincent's Hospital.

289
00:20:26,450 --> 00:20:29,200
I'm your doctor.
Try not to talk.

290
00:20:32,750 --> 00:20:33,900
My God.

291
00:20:33,900 --> 00:20:36,500
I'm paralyzed. I'm paralyzed!

292
00:20:36,600 --> 00:20:40,100
If you're moving your arms and legs,
you're clearly not paralyzed.

293
00:20:41,150 --> 00:20:42,350
Boo!

294
00:20:44,200 --> 00:20:45,950
Yes, thank you.
There's my flashlight.

295
00:20:46,000 --> 00:20:48,250
Thank you.
How's our patient doing?

296
00:20:48,350 --> 00:20:52,050
- It was touch and go for a while.
- Was it? What do you recommend?

297
00:20:53,250 --> 00:20:55,150
I think she needs more fluids.

298
00:20:55,250 --> 00:20:58,200
Why don't you go load her up
with 10 cc's of Yoo-Hoo, all right?

299
00:20:58,300 --> 00:20:59,500
Here we go.

300
00:21:02,550 --> 00:21:04,300
- You're the guy--
- Steve Edison.

301
00:21:04,400 --> 00:21:06,500
I'm the supervising
pediatrician here.

302
00:21:06,550 --> 00:21:09,900
- Mary--
- Fiore. Yeah, I know.

303
00:21:09,950 --> 00:21:12,250
I had to go through your wallet
to get your identification.

304
00:21:12,300 --> 00:21:15,000
I must say, I've never met anyone who
alphabetized her credit cards before.

305
00:21:16,850 --> 00:21:18,900
Here's the skinny on you.

306
00:21:18,950 --> 00:21:22,550
Your X-rays are fine.
Hemoglobin levels are normal.

307
00:21:22,650 --> 00:21:26,150
We're just waiting on the CAT scan to
be processed, then we can get you out of here.

308
00:21:26,200 --> 00:21:28,650
You can take this off now.

309
00:21:29,700 --> 00:21:32,250
- Oh, you've got a big neck.
- I have a big neck?

310
00:21:32,350 --> 00:21:34,750
Don't get me wrong.
It's a fine neck.

311
00:21:34,800 --> 00:21:38,200
It's just that haven't had a patient
over the age of six in three years.

312
00:21:47,800 --> 00:21:49,850
What happened to your hand?

313
00:21:50,850 --> 00:21:54,850
My hand. You fell on it
with your big neck.

314
00:22:32,050 --> 00:22:34,650
Your CAT scan came back,
and it's all clear.

315
00:22:35,750 --> 00:22:37,700
- So I'm okay?
- You're better than new.

316
00:22:39,800 --> 00:22:44,400
Speaking of new, that's a pretty
modern girl you have there.

317
00:22:44,450 --> 00:22:46,550
- Who?
- Your girlfriend.

318
00:22:48,500 --> 00:22:52,500
No, that's my sister.
I guess you could say she's modern.

319
00:22:52,600 --> 00:22:56,050
The last time I saw her,
she had a spike through her chin.

320
00:22:56,150 --> 00:22:57,150
Oh, my.

321
00:22:58,500 --> 00:23:01,300
What I don't understand
is how she got near the dumpster!

322
00:23:01,400 --> 00:23:02,950
Miss?

323
00:23:03,000 --> 00:23:05,800
- Oh, my God, you're alive!
- How did you find me?

324
00:23:05,850 --> 00:23:09,400
I'm so happy! The nurse found my
phone number taped to your Palm Pilot.

325
00:23:09,500 --> 00:23:12,100
She told me what happened, and--

326
00:23:14,350 --> 00:23:16,750
Is this the guy who saved you?

327
00:23:18,750 --> 00:23:22,150
I wouldn't exactly
call it a rescue.

328
00:23:22,250 --> 00:23:24,800
I mean, I was just in the right place
at the right time.

329
00:23:25,650 --> 00:23:28,900
Well, aren't you just
the modern-day hero?

330
00:23:36,600 --> 00:23:37,800
Are you okay?

331
00:23:43,450 --> 00:23:45,550
Fabulous.

332
00:23:45,600 --> 00:23:47,650
Penny Nicholson.
Nice to meet you.

333
00:23:47,750 --> 00:23:51,650
I'm Steve Edison.
It's nice to meet you too.

334
00:23:51,750 --> 00:23:54,400
Please, have a seat. Make yourself comfortable.
Mary's gonna be fine.

335
00:23:54,450 --> 00:23:59,150
So, you must work long hours.
Are you working late tonight?

336
00:23:59,250 --> 00:24:01,400
No, I'm not even on duty tonight.

337
00:24:02,350 --> 00:24:03,800
Great!

338
00:24:05,150 --> 00:24:08,050
You know, Mary and I were
gonna go to Golden Gate Park.

339
00:24:08,150 --> 00:24:10,650
They show old movies
on the side of the museum.

340
00:24:10,700 --> 00:24:12,600
And... you should come with us.

341
00:24:12,700 --> 00:24:16,850
- We won't take no for an answer.
- Penny, will you leave him alone, please?

342
00:24:16,950 --> 00:24:19,000
Oh, you don't want me to go?

343
00:24:19,900 --> 00:24:22,400
Of course she wants you to go.

344
00:24:23,750 --> 00:24:27,550
You know, the truth is, doctor...

345
00:24:27,600 --> 00:24:31,250
that I've-- I've been thinking
about a career in medicine.

346
00:24:31,300 --> 00:24:34,550
Something medicinal or whatnot.

347
00:24:34,600 --> 00:24:38,050
I'd really like to
just pick a part of your brain.

348
00:24:38,100 --> 00:24:40,150
- Do not leave me here.
- I know what's best for you.

349
00:24:40,250 --> 00:24:42,150
I'm gonna get you over this Keith thing
once and for all!

350
00:24:42,250 --> 00:24:44,300
It's only been six years.

351
00:24:44,400 --> 00:24:46,350
It's not a date!

352
00:24:46,400 --> 00:24:48,750
Do not leave me alone. Please.

353
00:24:48,850 --> 00:24:51,100
- It's for your own good.
- Don't you dare!

354
00:24:52,800 --> 00:24:54,850
- There he is.
- There's your gum ball.

355
00:24:54,900 --> 00:24:58,450
Thank you. Oh, good. Boy, you
can never get the colors you want.

356
00:24:58,500 --> 00:24:59,950
Okay, well.

357
00:25:01,100 --> 00:25:03,000
Oh, no!

358
00:25:03,100 --> 00:25:05,600
Darn it. I just remembered
that I-- I promised...

359
00:25:05,700 --> 00:25:09,500
my friend's brother's godmother...

360
00:25:09,550 --> 00:25:12,400
that I would help her...

361
00:25:12,500 --> 00:25:15,400
change her fax cartridge tonight...

362
00:25:15,500 --> 00:25:18,800
because she's going
out of town tomorrow...

363
00:25:18,850 --> 00:25:20,450
on an African safari.

364
00:25:21,450 --> 00:25:23,350
I should go do that.

365
00:25:23,450 --> 00:25:26,100
I'm really sorry that we're not
gonna be able to have that...

366
00:25:26,150 --> 00:25:27,900
- medical chat.
- Medical chat, yeah.

367
00:25:31,900 --> 00:25:34,400
Okay. Bye.

368
00:25:34,450 --> 00:25:36,250
- Penny.
- Wow.

369
00:25:36,350 --> 00:25:38,450
Goodness, I hope her...

370
00:25:39,600 --> 00:25:43,500
friend's brother's godmother
is gonna be okay.

371
00:25:43,500 --> 00:25:46,300
You know,
I have reserved seating.

372
00:25:46,350 --> 00:25:48,650
- All right.
- Okay. Let's go.

373
00:25:50,850 --> 00:25:53,800
- Thanks for guarding my tree.
- Yes, I'm guarding your tree.

374
00:25:53,850 --> 00:25:56,150
There's your blanket right there
under your tree I kept for you.

375
00:25:56,200 --> 00:25:59,400
- Thank you, Burt. This is Steve Edison.
- Steve, how you do? Nice to meet you.

376
00:25:59,500 --> 00:26:01,600
- Pleased to meet you.
- It's about time you had a date.

377
00:26:01,650 --> 00:26:04,200
- It's not--
- What line of business are you in?

378
00:26:04,250 --> 00:26:06,850
- I'm a doctor at St. Vincent's.
- You a doctor?

379
00:26:06,950 --> 00:26:09,500
He's a doctor.
Well, I get the hint.

380
00:26:09,600 --> 00:26:12,200
See you at the Scrabble
practice, kid.

381
00:26:13,600 --> 00:26:16,950
Sorry. I'm so sorry about that.

382
00:26:17,000 --> 00:26:19,200
Scrabble practice?

383
00:26:19,300 --> 00:26:21,200
Please, don't ask.

384
00:26:21,300 --> 00:26:23,350
Come on. You can't
leave me hanging on that.

385
00:26:23,450 --> 00:26:27,900
"See you at Scrabble practice, kid"?
What's that?

386
00:26:28,000 --> 00:26:30,350
I'm a member of
the Bay Area Scrabble Club.

387
00:26:30,400 --> 00:26:32,950
- Pathetic, I know.
- Wow.

388
00:26:33,050 --> 00:26:35,400
- What?
- That is pathetic.

389
00:26:35,450 --> 00:26:37,850
Shut up.

390
00:26:37,900 --> 00:26:40,650
At least I can spell.
What can you do?

391
00:26:40,750 --> 00:26:43,400
- I throw a mean yo-yo.
- You know what?

392
00:26:43,450 --> 00:26:47,000
- No more caramel corn for you.
- I'm serious.

393
00:26:47,100 --> 00:26:50,400
How'd you get into it? I've never met
a member of a Scrabble Club before.

394
00:26:50,500 --> 00:26:52,400
That's for sure.

395
00:26:54,350 --> 00:26:57,350
When my parents came over
from Italy...

396
00:26:57,400 --> 00:27:00,450
they joined a Scrabble Club
so they could learn English.

397
00:27:01,500 --> 00:27:05,950
And after my mom died, my dad became,
like, obsessed with the game...

398
00:27:06,000 --> 00:27:08,500
and wanted me to play with him
all the time...

399
00:27:08,600 --> 00:27:11,250
so I guess, in a way,
I was destined.

400
00:27:12,550 --> 00:27:14,500
C-O-O-L.

401
00:27:22,800 --> 00:27:24,300
What are you doing?

402
00:27:27,800 --> 00:27:29,800
I only eat the brown ones.

403
00:27:29,850 --> 00:27:31,300
Because?

404
00:27:32,600 --> 00:27:35,400
'Cause I figure they have
less artificial coloring...

405
00:27:35,400 --> 00:27:38,700
'cause chocolate's already brown.

406
00:27:38,800 --> 00:27:41,000
That's very scientific of you,
dr. Steve.

407
00:27:41,100 --> 00:27:42,250
Thank you, Mary.

408
00:27:46,050 --> 00:27:48,150
So where would one go
to see a Scrabble match?

409
00:27:48,250 --> 00:27:51,000
Oh, look. It's starting.

410
00:27:57,050 --> 00:28:01,800
And closer

411
00:28:01,850 --> 00:28:05,450
tome

412
00:28:10,900 --> 00:28:13,400
- Oh, that's beautiful.
- You like it?

413
00:28:13,500 --> 00:28:14,950
Yes.

414
00:28:29,300 --> 00:28:33,600
This is by far the coolest thing
I've ever done in this city.

415
00:28:37,750 --> 00:28:42,050
the closer you are

416
00:28:42,050 --> 00:28:46,550
- the brighter the stars glow
- Wanna dance?

417
00:28:46,600 --> 00:28:51,350
I don't know. I haven't danced
in quite some time.

418
00:28:51,400 --> 00:28:54,900
- Okay.
- Girl asks you to dance, you dance.

419
00:28:57,300 --> 00:29:00,900
Burt's right.
Yes, Mary, I would love to dance.

420
00:29:02,350 --> 00:29:05,500
- No pressure.
- It's too late now.

421
00:29:13,700 --> 00:29:15,100
Okay.

422
00:29:23,450 --> 00:29:26,400
Where'd you learn
to dance like this?

423
00:29:26,450 --> 00:29:28,600
Ballroom class.

424
00:29:28,600 --> 00:29:30,900
Oh, you're gay.

425
00:29:30,950 --> 00:29:33,250
Oh, yeah, the gayest.

426
00:29:38,800 --> 00:29:42,250
My mother put me
in ballroom classes...

427
00:29:42,350 --> 00:29:44,300
when I was eight years old.

428
00:29:44,350 --> 00:29:47,900
She wanted me to be Fred Astaire.
I wanted to be Marcus Welby.

429
00:29:49,500 --> 00:29:52,250
So now you're
a little bit of both?

430
00:29:54,400 --> 00:29:56,500
I think you're being kind.

431
00:29:56,550 --> 00:29:59,400
You can stop that.
I'm gonna blush.

432
00:30:03,950 --> 00:30:05,850
How's your thumb?

433
00:30:07,300 --> 00:30:08,700
Never better.

434
00:30:30,200 --> 00:30:32,100
YMCA.

435
00:30:32,200 --> 00:30:34,900
My next Scrabble match
is Saturday...

436
00:30:34,950 --> 00:30:38,000
at 1:00 at the north side YMCA.

437
00:30:38,050 --> 00:30:40,550
It'll be the social event
of the season.

438
00:30:42,000 --> 00:30:44,350
Maybe you should be there.

439
00:30:48,500 --> 00:30:51,750
- Maybe you shouldn't step on my foot.
- Did I?

440
00:30:51,800 --> 00:30:53,350
- Yes.
- I'm sorry.

441
00:30:53,400 --> 00:30:55,550
That's okay.
Just don't let it happen again.

442
00:30:57,400 --> 00:30:58,900
Don't tell me what to do.

443
00:30:58,950 --> 00:31:00,350
Don't what?

444
00:31:37,000 --> 00:31:38,600
Holy shit!

445
00:31:38,650 --> 00:31:41,100
Are you guys crazy?
This isn't funny!

446
00:31:41,150 --> 00:31:44,750
I am thinking teal for the bridesmaids.
What do you think?

447
00:31:47,100 --> 00:31:49,450
Good morning. Earth to Mary.

448
00:31:49,500 --> 00:31:52,000
What is up with you?
You're different.

449
00:31:52,100 --> 00:31:54,600
I'm not different.
How am I different?

450
00:31:54,700 --> 00:31:56,700
You can't stop smiling.

451
00:31:58,100 --> 00:32:00,100
I'm not smiling.
Am I smiling?

452
00:32:00,200 --> 00:32:02,450
Like a fool.

453
00:32:02,500 --> 00:32:04,850
- Tell me.
- It's nothing.

454
00:32:04,950 --> 00:32:07,450
Then stop smiling.

455
00:32:07,550 --> 00:32:10,250
- I can't.
- Okay, who is he?

456
00:32:15,400 --> 00:32:17,350
Okay. No, no!

457
00:32:17,400 --> 00:32:20,700
Mr. Kotsioupolis, you cannot throw
plates at the Ritz-fucking-Carlton!

458
00:32:21,800 --> 00:32:22,950
It's okay.

459
00:32:23,050 --> 00:32:24,800
This is like a fairy tale.

460
00:32:24,900 --> 00:32:27,400
He saves your life.
You dance under the stars.

461
00:32:27,450 --> 00:32:30,150
- You kiss in the rain.
- Almost kissed.

462
00:32:30,250 --> 00:32:34,350
I don't know, Fran. I've been so out
of the whole dating-relationship loop.

463
00:32:34,450 --> 00:32:35,750
You?

464
00:32:35,800 --> 00:32:40,000
You know, those who can't do, teach?
Those who can't wed, plan.

465
00:32:40,100 --> 00:32:43,000
With my help, you could marry
this man in three months.

466
00:32:43,900 --> 00:32:47,150
I have totally lost control.
Will you please, please, please help me?

467
00:32:47,250 --> 00:32:49,100
Penny, if you can't beat 'em--

468
00:32:50,250 --> 00:32:52,950
- What has gotten into you?
- She met a guy.

469
00:32:53,050 --> 00:32:55,850
You met a guy? You mean--

470
00:33:01,100 --> 00:33:04,350
- I wanna hear all about it!
- I owe you one, Penny.

471
00:33:04,400 --> 00:33:06,500
You do. You owe me one!

472
00:33:08,750 --> 00:33:11,650
- Hello, Rene. How are you?
- Great.

473
00:33:11,750 --> 00:33:14,200
Listen, they're gonna be
signing up for six classes.

474
00:33:14,250 --> 00:33:16,950
So just be sure
to pay up front, okay?

475
00:33:16,950 --> 00:33:19,200
Basil himself
is gonna be here today.

476
00:33:19,250 --> 00:33:21,200
- Really?
- Yes.

477
00:33:23,200 --> 00:33:25,700
I'll have to call you back.
Okay. Bye.

478
00:33:27,100 --> 00:33:29,350
Mary, what are you doing here?

479
00:33:29,450 --> 00:33:31,800
Oh, my God.
I'm so embarrassed.

480
00:33:31,900 --> 00:33:33,800
I may be a hell
of a businesswoman...

481
00:33:33,850 --> 00:33:36,800
but when I dance,
I look like a retarded string bean.

482
00:33:36,900 --> 00:33:38,900
I thought your class
wasn't till Thursday though.

483
00:33:39,000 --> 00:33:41,700
I know. We had to change it.
But this is perfect.

484
00:33:41,750 --> 00:33:45,100
You can finally meet Eddie.
Come here. Eddie.

485
00:33:45,200 --> 00:33:47,150
Eddie, come here.

486
00:33:47,200 --> 00:33:49,250
I want you to meet
the wedding planner.

487
00:33:49,300 --> 00:33:52,000
The two most important people
in my life set eyes on one another.

488
00:33:52,100 --> 00:33:54,500
Eddie, this is Mary,
the wedding planner.

489
00:33:55,300 --> 00:33:57,200
Mary, this is my fiance Eddie.

490
00:34:10,350 --> 00:34:14,050
- Mary, are you okay?
- Uh-huh. Yup. Good.

